Title: War for the Planet of the Apes | Teaser Trailer [HD] | 20th Century FOX
Comment:
Hahahaha... I'm sorry, are they serious? Look, I get that apes are preternaturally stronger than us, but they ain't bulletproof. When a culture with bronze swords met a culture with steel swords, the people with bronze were easily defeated. You think spears can penetrate ceramic armour? You think apes can dodge bullets?

History has shown us that every time one culture meets another the degree of difference in weapons technology determines the outcome. This is great stuff, but the first reboot had the right idea. The plague makes humans dumb, and apes smarter.  Then the sequel was silly, but fun, but now they're just plain stupid.

Title: War for the Planet of the Apes | Teaser Trailer [HD] | 20th Century FOX
Comment:
SPOILER ALERT: 


YOU'VE BEEN WARNED!






The virus that killed most of the human race is still having an effect on the world.  The virus is making apes all over the world smarter and giving them the ability to speak like Caesar.  On the other hand, the virus is having the opposite effect on the children born from the human "survivors" of the virus.  It is making them less intelligent and taking away their ability to speak.  Until a cure can be found, the humans have decided to kill all their children affected by the virus in order to preserve the species' good genetics.  Unfortunately, no human child has been able to avoid the effects of the virus. The Colonel's son was killed for this reason.  During Caesar's journey to find the colonel, Caesar encounters a human army deserter and kills him in self defense.  Apparently, this man deserted in order to keep his daughter, who was affected by the virus and cannot speak, alive.  A reluctant Caesar and his group take the girl with them in order to save her, but Caesar also thinks he can use her as a possible bargaining chip.  At this point, Caesar has no idea about the virus and what effects it is currently having on the humans.  Because, the human race is essentially becoming extinct due to the virus, and apes are evolving and becoming smarter, the humans have decided that the only way they can survive is by wiping out all apes so they can buy more time to come up with a cure for their current condition.  The humans fear that even if they do find a cure, it will be too late because the apes will have taken over if left unchecked.  Some of the humans do not believe in the war and do not agree with the order to kill the children.  Therefore, they eventually become allies with Caesar, who after finding empathy for humans again, decides to help them.  A conflict ensues between the human army and the human/ape army.  In the end, the human armies destroy themselves, and the apes take over.  In the next movie, with the human species on the ropes, Koba's followers begin a genocidal campaign to wipe out the remaining humans.  Caesar allies with the remaining humans in order to fight an Ape super army.  Caesar and the humans also discover that Caesar is the key to a cure for the virus, as he was the original host of the disease.    After the Koba apes discover that Caesar holds the cure for the virus, they plot to assassinate him.  Of course, Caesar is eventually murdered by those he trusts ("et tu, Luca?"), and with no hope of manufacturing a cure because of Caesar's demise, the humans decide to nuke the planet.  In the end, almost all of the human race, which still resided in human cities throughout the word, was wiped out, and the Apes, who mostly lived in rural areas, were able to avoid the nuclear destruction and take over the world and enslave/kill what little remains of the human race. Thousands of years later the original POTA story begins.

Comment:
Dawn of the Apes was a movie I liked even more after I had a chance to reflect on it after the first viewing. I appreciated how all of the characters involved in the arc of the story had motivations that made you feel empathy for them. 

I can't tell if this one is going to be as nuanced: on the surface, it's bigger and louder, with more tanks and more guns. But filling the 2 hours in between will be Mark Bomback and Matt Reeves' script, and by my account, Reeves hasn't failed yet (Cloverfield, Let Me In, and Dawn of the Apes is a pretty good studio run).

Title: War for the Planet of the Apes | Teaser Trailer [HD] | 20th Century FOX
Comment: Great movies, but I can never suspend my disbelief enough to fully enjoy them. The problem isn't with the apes being smart, but with humans being immensely incompetent. We would just carpet bomb every single city and mountain that the apes occupy, and that would be that. A single missile could level their entire encampment, and then some. In the previous movie, it would be impossible for the monkeys to overrun an entrenched position defended with guns, especially a 50cal. Doesn't matter how smart they are or how high they jump.

Comment: One of my most anticipated movies of 2017. I absolutely LOVED Rise and Dawn. I even thought Dawn deserved an Oscar nom, or at least Andy Serkis. What I love about these movies are, they're not just brainless action movies, they have strong messages in them, phenomenal actors in each one (Woody Harrelson as the main villain?? 😱), great drama, and amazing special effects that's used to perfection. And watching the progression of Caesar's character over three movies is something you rarely see done so well in franchises nowadays. They really knocked it out of the park with these prequels and I couldn't be more appreciative.

Title: War for the Planet of the Apes | Teaser Trailer [HD] | 20th Century FOX
Comment:
Finally - a movie with a big budget, that isn't just more Marvel/DC/Jedi/superhero expanded universe brain-numbing franchising, that all more or less just feel like the same movie, and usually ends with some CGI-infested showdown around a blue laser shooting up into the sky in a big city. 
These "of the Apes"-movies are more or less some of the last big budgeted block buster movies, that feel intelligent, dark, gritty and like their own movies, while still getting a big budget.
I really hope we're going to see more movies like these again, and less Marvel (and all their imitators) movies that just keep repeating themselves while feeling like an unrealistic extended a toy-commercial.
